solutions.content:
It is quite hard to understand the requirements at first, but the animation makes it easier.
So, we know in advance that we will be having an array of strings of length *n*, and therefore
the constructor allocates a vector of empty strings. That is quite easy.

Inserting a value is also easy, since it is guaranteed, by the problem description, that each pair
will have a unique *id*. You just replace the empty string on a position given by *idKey* (-1, since
we count from 0) with string *value*.

Now comes the tricky part. Upon each insertion, you need to return a list of strings such that it
is a continuos chunk, with no empty strings between them. You start off from index *lastIndex*, and in a 
aux buffer you *push_back* all non-empty strings that come afterwards, and you increment *lastIndex*
after each push. Also, pay attention that you cannot check *arr.at(lastIndex)* if *lastIndex* is out of range.
That will throw you a runtime error which is hard to figure out. That's why you need *lastIndex < arr.size()*.

No dynamic allocation, so no destructor is needed.


```
class OrderedStream {
public:
    OrderedStream(int n) : arr {vector<string>(n, "")} 
    {
    }

    vector<string> insert(int idKey, string value) 
    {
        arr.at(idKey-1) = value;  

        vector<string> ret{};

        while (lastIndex < arr.size() && arr.at(lastIndex) != "")
        {
            ret.push_back(arr.at(lastIndex++));
        }

        return ret;
    }

private:
    vector<string> arr;
    int lastIndex{0};
};
```

Thanks to [@RedaKerouicha](https://leetcode.com/RedaKerouicha) for pointing out that *vector<string> arr{};* should be *vector<string> arr;* since we initialize it in the constructor.

