solutions.content:
## Intuition
Rule 1 means that the ordering of the letters is irrelevant.
Rule 2 means that the overall population of occurences has to be the same, but doesn't have to map to the same letters.

For example `latter` has 4 letters (aler) occuring 1 time, and 1 (t) occuring 2 times.  `taller` also has 4 letters (taer) occuring 1 time and 1 (l) occuring 4 times.  These 2 strings are close.

Just be sure that all the letters from the first word occur at least once in the second word, and vice versa.

## Approach

- Frequency map both strings (we're interested in counts of letters here).
- Verify that no letter occurs in just 1 string.
- Sort the frequency mappings.
- Verify that the mappings are the same.

## Complexity
- Time complexity: $O(n)$

- Space complexity: $O(1)$

Keep in mind that this involves sorting, but the arrays sorted are a fixed length of 26.
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

## Code
